<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-linear-transformations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" >
  <title>Linear Transformations</title>
<section xml:id="section-3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Definition and Properties</title>
  <p>
    In this section, we will discuss linear transformations and their properties.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="Matrix-Transformation">
    <title>Transformation by Matrix Multiplication</title>
    <statement>
     <p>Consider the matrix
     <m> A = \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
2 \amp 1 \amp 0 
\end{array}
\right]
     </m>
     By matrix multiplication, <m>A</m> maps vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> into vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> as shown below. Consider the vector 
<m>\vec{X} = \left[\begin{array}{c}
x \\
y \\
z
\end{array}
\right]</m>, then the image of <m>\vec{X}</m> under the transformation defined by <m>A</m> is given by:
<me>A\vec{X} = \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
2 \amp 1 \amp 0 
\end{array}
\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
x \\
y \\
z
\end{array}\right] = \left[\begin{array}{c}
x + 2y \\
2x + y
\end{array}\right]</me>  
     </p>
    </statement>
 </example>

   <definition xml:id="def-linear-transformation">
      <statement>
        <p>A transformation <m>T:\R^n\rightarrow \R^m</m> is a 
          linear transformation if it satisfies the following two 
          properties for all <m>\vec{x},\vec{y}\in\R^n</m> and all 
          scalars <m>a\in \R</m>.
         <ol>
          <li>Preservation of vector addition: <m>T(\vec{x}+\vec{y})=T(\vec{x})+T(\vec{y})</m></li>
          <li>Preservation of scalar multiplication: <m>T(a\vec{x})=aT(\vec{x})</m></li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark xml:id="remark-properties-linear-transformations">
      <title>Properties of Linear Transformations</title>
      <p>Let <m>T:\R^n\to\R^m</m> be a linear transformation, and
let <m>\vec{x}\in\R^n</m>.
Since <m>T</m> preserves scalar multiplication,
<ol>
<li> <m>T(0\vec{x})=0T(\vec{x})</m> implying <m>T(\vec{0})=\vec{0}</m>, 
so <m>T</m> preserves the zero vector.</li>
<li> <m>T((-1)\vec{x})=(-1)T(\vec{x})</m>, implying <m>T(-\vec{x})=-T(\vec{x})</m>,
so <m>T</m> preserves the negative of a vector.
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</remark>
  </section>
</chapter>